Basic Metropolis-Hastings MCMC¶

Sample using Markov Chain Monte Carlo steps on a tractable approximating distribution $Q(x';x)$ and accept new samples/steps with probability $\min\rb{1,\frac{P(x')Q(x;x')}{P(x)Q(x';x)}}$.

1D case¶

In [2]:
# M-H params
S = 10000 # run most of these for 100,000+ iterations after verifying the notebook is configured correctly

# true distribution setup
sigmas = [0.1, 1, 100]
p = norm(loc=0,scale=1)

def metropolis(x, sigma):
    # single metropolis-hastings step/sample
    x_ = npr.normal(x,sigma)
    p_accept = (p.pdf(x_)*norm.pdf(x,x_,sigma))/(p.pdf(x)*norm.pdf(x_,x,sigma))
    accept = npr.rand(1) < p_accept
    return (x_ if accept else x), accept
    
fig, ax = plt.subplots(3,2)
samples = np.zeros((3,S))
accepts = np.zeros((3,S))
for i in np.arange(0,3):
    for n in np.arange(1,S):
        x = npr.normal(0, sigmas[i])
        samples[i,n], accepts[i,n] = metropolis(samples[i,n-1], sigmas[i])
        if n % 1000 == 0 or n == S - 1:
            ax[i,0].clear()
            ax[i,0].scatter(np.arange(n), accepts[i,:n], alpha = 0.75, color='orange', s=2, label='Accept/Reject')
            ax[i,0].plot(np.arange(n), samples[i,:n], alpha = 0.75, color='blue', label='Samples')
            ax[i,0].set_title("Sigma = {}".format(sigmas[i]))
            ax[i,0].legend()
            
            ax[i,1].clear()
            ax[i,1].set_title("Accept = {}".format(accepts[i,:n].mean()))
            _, bins, _ = ax[i,1].hist(samples[i,:n], bins=30, density=True)
            y = p.pdf(bins)
            ax[i,1].plot(bins, y, alpha=0.5)
            
            fig.canvas.draw()
            time.sleep(0.01)
plt.show()

Acceptance drops as the approximating distribution becomes worse (when the true sigma is more divergent from $Q$'s)

def plot2d(n, title, samples, contourZ, fig, ax):
    ax.clear()
    ax.set_title(title)
    ax.contourf(x,y,contourZ(pos), 20, cmap=plt.cm.bone)
    ax.plot(samples[:,0], samples[:,1], color='red', alpha = 0.05)
    ax.scatter(samples[:,0], samples[:,1], color='red', alpha = 0.2, s=0.3)
    ax.set_aspect(1)
    fig.canvas.draw()
    time.sleep(0.01)

# M-H params

# true distribution setup
mu = np.array([0,0])
Sigma = np.array([[0.5, 1],[0.5,1]])
p = mvn(mean=mu,cov=Sigma)
p2 = mvn(mean=np.array([1,1]),cov=Sigma*0.35)
p3 = mvn(mean=np.array([-1,-1]),cov=Sigma*0.39)
p4 = lambda x: p3.pdf(x) + p2.pdf(x)
p=p4

# contour plot setup
N = 30
xax = np.linspace(-3,3,N)
yax = np.linspace(-3,3,N)
x,y = np.meshgrid(xax,yax)
pos = np.empty(x.shape + (2,))
pos[:, :, 0] = x
pos[:, :, 1] = y

    
def metropolis_xy(x, Sigma):
    x_ = mvn.rvs(mean=x,cov=sigma)
    p_accept = (p(x_)*mvn.pdf(x,x_,Sigma))/(p(x)*mvn.pdf(x_,x,Sigma))
    accept = npr.rand(1) < p_accept
    return (x_ if accept else x), accept

samples = np.zeros((3,S,2))
accepts = np.zeros((3,S))
for i in np.arange(0,3):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(5,5))
    sigma = sigmas[i]
    for n in np.arange(1,S):
        samples[i,n], accepts[i,n] = metropolis_xy(samples[i,n-1], sigma)
        if n % 100 == 0 or n == S - 1:
            plot2d(n, "Sigma = {}, accept = {:.4f}".format(sigmas[i], accepts[i,:n].mean()), samples[i], lambda x: (np.log(p(x))), fig, ax)
plt.show()

Hamiltonian Monte Carlo¶

Sampling using discretized Hamiltonian dynamics for high-dimension black box problems where we have a gradient.

In [6]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import autograd.numpy as np
import autograd.numpy.random as npr
import autograd.scipy.stats.norm as ag_norm
import autograd.scipy.stats.multivariate_normal as ag_mvn
from autograd import grad
In [7]:
# Insights taken from https://github.com/ANC-PIGlets/gradient-based-mcmc/blob/master/Hamiltonian%20Monte%20Carlo.ipynb
# and http://homepages.inf.ed.ac.uk/imurray2/teaching/09mlss/slides.pdf
def ham(x, v):
    # Hamiltonian of position x and velocity v
    # need to introduce M matrix to leapfrog steps if inner product 
    # other than dot is used here
    # eg we are in some other space
    return -E(x) + (v.dot(v)*0.5)

def leapfrog(x, v, steps, eps, dEdx):
    # partially optimized leapfrog method for Hamiltonian MCMC
    # see e.g. "MCMC using Hamiltonian dynamics" Neal, p. 10
    
    v -= (eps/2) * dEdx(x) # initial half step
    for i in range(steps-1): # full size steps
        x += eps * v
        v -= eps * dEdx(x)
    x += eps * v # final full step
    v -= (eps/2) * dEdx(x) # final half step
    return x, v

def hamilton_metropolis(x, v, eps, E, dEdx, phi, steps):
    # Take a Hamiltonian Metropolis-Hastings sample
    # leapfrog to simulate hamiltonian dynamics for a time step
    x_, v_ = leapfrog(x.copy(), v.copy(), steps, eps, dEdx) 
    # hamiltonian of proposed move
    prop_ham = ham(x_, v_) 
    # probability of accepting proposed move
    accept = (rs.uniform() < np.minimum(1, np.exp(ham(x, v) - ham(x_, v_)))) 
    # accept move (or reject and reverse velocity)
    out_x, out_v = ((x_, v_) if accept else (x, -v))
    # resample velocity and interpolate if sin(phi) > 0
    out_v = np.cos(phi) * rs.normal(size=x.size) + np.sin(phi) * out_v
    return (out_x, out_v, accept)

1D case¶

In [8]:
# MCMC params
S = 10000
phi = 3.1415/4
steps = [1, 1, 5]
eps = [0.1, 0.5, 4]

# True distribution params
sigmas = [0.1, 1, 100]
rs = npr.RandomState(19823)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(3,3)

samples = np.zeros((3,S,1))
velocities = np.zeros((3,S,1))
accepts = np.zeros((3,S))
for i in np.arange(0,3):
    E = (lambda x: ag_norm.logpdf(x, loc=0, scale=sigmas[i]))
    dEdx = grad(E)
    
    # initialize MCMC values
    samples[0] = rs.normal(0, sigmas[i], (1,))
    velocities[0] =  rs.normal(0, 1, (1,))

    for n in np.arange(1,S):
        samples[i,n], velocities[i,n], accepts[i,n] = hamilton_metropolis(
            samples[i,n-1], 
            velocities[i,n-1], 
            eps[i],
            E,
            dEdx,
            phi,
            steps[i]
        )
        
        if n % 1000 == 0:
            ax[i,0].clear()
            ax[i,1].clear()
            ax[i,2].clear()
            
            ax[i,1].set_ylim(sigmas[i]*-2, sigmas[i]*2)
            #ax[i].scatter(np.arange(S), accepts[i], alpha = 0.75, color='orange', s=2)
            ax[i,0].plot(np.arange(n), samples[i,:n], alpha = 0.75, color='blue')
            ax[i,1].plot(np.arange(n), samples[i,:n], alpha = 0.75, color='green')
            ax[i,1].set_title("Accept = {}".format(accepts[i,:].mean()))
            ax[i,2].set_xlim(sigmas[i]*-2, sigmas[i]*2)
            _, bins, _ = ax[i,2].hist(samples[i,:n], bins=30, density=True)
            y = ag_norm.pdf(bins, loc=0, scale=sigmas[i])
            ax[i,2].plot(bins, y, alpha=0.5)
            
            fig.canvas.draw()
            time.sleep(0.05)

# true distribution setup

Sigma = np.array([[0.6, 0.4],[0.4,0.6]])
p4 = lambda x: np.log(
    ag_mvn.pdf(x,mean=np.array([3,2]),cov=Sigma*0.6) + 
    ag_mvn.pdf(x,mean=np.array([-1,-1]),cov=Sigma*0.39)
)
E=p4
dEdx = grad(E)
rs = npr.RandomState(31)


# contour grid plot setup around true distribution
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,1)
offset = 10
N = 50
mid = np.array([2,2])
xax = np.linspace(mu[0] - Sigma[0,0] * offset,mu[0] + Sigma[0,0] * offset, N)
yax = np.linspace(mu[1] - Sigma[1,1] * offset,mu[1] + Sigma[1,1] * offset, N)
x,y = np.meshgrid(xax,yax)
pos = np.empty(x.shape + (2,))
pos[:, :, 0] = x
pos[:, :, 1] = y


samples = np.zeros((S,2))
velocities = np.zeros((S,2))
accepts = np.zeros((S))

# initialize MCMC values
samples[0] = rs.multivariate_normal([0,0], Sigma, 1)
velocities[0] = rs.multivariate_normal([0,0], [[1,0],[0,1]], 1)
for n in np.arange(1,S):
    samples[n], velocities[n], accepts[n] = hamilton_metropolis(
        samples[n-1],

        dEdx,
        phi,
        1

    if n % 1000 == 0:
